			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=56398&amp;sid=96206ca02616df4d7d03a68c138eb206#56398"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Mar 25, 2004 7:43 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Question from a first time homeowner</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=56398&amp;sid=96206ca02616df4d7d03a68c138eb206"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Your sears card will run about 21% interest. Your other credit cards will usually run somewhat less. Last time I owned a place, I shopped at Best Buys for appliances, but then I was looking for the stainless steel look (the items being replaced were gold and avacado: popular colors from the 70s) because I had been planning to renovate the kitchen, and SS fits in with a lot of other color and cabinet possibilities. Selzer water is great for cleaning stainless. Most fridges last 15+ years, some for 30+. I would recommend staying away from gadgets like touch screens and internet connectivity. Look for energy efficiency also. An efficient fridge will use a lot less juice in the next 15 years than something that has little insulation. The most efficient fridges are marketed to folks who have only solar/wind power and can run on about $10 of electricity per year for a full size fridge. The ones you see in the stores are probably using $100-$300. The fridges from the early 70s / late 60s are probably using about $500-$1000 per year of electricity. 
<br />

<br />
If you eat a lot of frozen pizzas, or sometimes buy large frozen things (like turkeys) a side-by-side is going to @#%$ you off in a couple of months. If you have kids, the handles for drink and ice dispensers have a short lifetime ( *slam* *snap* oops!). Some of the newer fridges have built in water filters. If the one you are putting in uses water, put in a good water filter (in a spot you can easily reach), and try to find some of those stainless steel water lines from Home Depot. Its a pain in the butt to replace a leaky line a few years down the road.
<br />

<br />
Use a tape measure to find the sizes of appliances you can use. When you go to the store, bring a note pad and pen with you to write down the stuff. Check out the consumer reports magazines at your library. If you eat frozen pizzas, cut out a piece of cardboard a little larger than the ones you buy, and bring that cardboard when you shop: so you can see if it will fit in your candidate fridge.
<br />

<br />
Good luck in your new home.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
